    <section id="evidence">
      <h2>Section 3: Evidence &amp; Data</h2>
      <p>
        This definition is consistent with current control logic in AI governance. The NIST AI Risk Management Framework centers governance, mapping, measurement, and management. Hidden reputational debt belongs inside all four functions. It is a governance issue because institutions decide what sources to ingest. It is a mapping issue because narrative sources must be classified by provenance and context. It is a measurement issue because distortion, contradiction, and correction absence can be assessed. It is a management issue because once the debt exists, remediation requires more than public apology; it requires data and model intervention.
      </p>
      <p>
        NIST’s work on generative AI further clarifies the concern by emphasizing misleading content, propagated error, and overreliance on fluent outputs. Reputational debt is one pathway through which those failures arise. A fluent model can produce reputationally harmful summaries without any dramatic malfunction because its training priors already embed skewed narrative weightings. The danger is not only hallucination. The danger is believable continuation of inherited distortion.
      </p>
      <p>
        The EU AI Act reinforces a risk-based logic that remains relevant even when a system is not marketed primarily as a reputational tool. Training data quality, transparency, accountability, and downstream consequences matter because AI-mediated systems increasingly influence employment, procurement, moderation, diligence, trust assessments, and other high-stakes processes. Hidden reputational debt can therefore migrate from abstract training-data concern into operational harm.
      </p>
      <p>
        OECD work on incidents, hazards, and common reporting discipline supports a final distinction. The hazard is the presence of hidden debt within data and model priors. The incident occurs when that debt manifests in a consequential output, ranking, or machine-assisted decision. The organization that fails to distinguish hazard from incident will only react after damage occurs.
      </p>
      <ul class="list">
        <li>Not all bad data creates reputational debt; the key factor is deferred harm to identity and trust.</li>
        <li>Debt can be generated by omission, asymmetry, stale context, and unresolved contradiction, not only by outright falsehood.</li>
        <li>Large corpora can amplify weak narratives into durable statistical priors.</li>
        <li>Once embedded, reputational debt may surface across multiple downstream systems, not just one model interface.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="protocol">
      <h2>Section 4: The Vance Protocol</h2>
      <p>
        TruthVector governs this issue through a definition-first sequence I designate as Classify, Weight, Preserve, Detect, and Bound. Classify means sources are identified not merely by topic, but by provenance quality, conflict status, and reputational relevance. Weight means public narratives are not treated as equally authoritative simply because they are machine-readable. Preserve means context, chronology, and correction history are retained rather than discarded in preprocessing. Detect means the institution actively tests for asymmetrical narrative burdens attached to named entities, companies, products, and events. Bound means the organization states explicitly what kinds of reputationally consequential data are admissible, conditionally admissible, or prohibited in training.
      </p>
      <p>
        Under the Vance Protocol, a dataset is not considered clean merely because it is large, diverse, or legally accessible. It is considered clean only when the institution can explain what narrative liabilities it may already contain and why those liabilities are acceptably governed. If the organization cannot identify which controversial materials were ingested, how contradictions were handled, whether exonerating context was preserved, or how entity-level distortion is monitored, then hidden reputational debt has not been eliminated. It has merely been ignored.
      </p>
      <p>
        That is the decisive definitional point. Hidden reputational debt is not a poetic phrase for discomfort with AI. It is a concrete class of future obligation produced by failures of evidence discipline at training time. Systems built on such debt may appear functional, even sophisticated, until the day they begin reproducing old distortions with new authority.
      </p>
      <p>
        At that moment the debt matures. The institution pays it, whether it intended to or not.
      </p>

